{"TopicId":145519,"ForumId":16,"TopicTitle":"Change polar angle","CreatedByName":"elstak","CreatedById":161716,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-08-07T00:20:32Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"elstak","CreatedById":161716,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-08-07T00:20:32Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHi,\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIm trying to change the polar angle but i cant found the value of polar angle (\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Mechjeb (mod)\u0022\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Mechjeb (mod)\u0022\u003EMJ\u003C/abbr\u003E\u003C/abbr\u003E or \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Kerbal Engineer Redux (mod)\u0022\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Kerbal Engineer Redux (mod)\u0022\u003EKER\u003C/abbr\u003E\u003C/abbr\u003E), dont confuse with the inclination (0/180 equatorial, 90/270 polar), see the picture to know what i mean.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022notittle.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 src=\u0022https://s8.postimg.org/nxrhwwbb9/notittle.png\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAnybody knows to found this value?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThanks\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222016-08-07T00:23:06Z\u0022 title=\u002208/07/2016 12:23  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00227 yr\u0022\u003EAugust 7, 2016\u003C/time\u003E by elstak\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Gaarst","CreatedById":126740,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-08-07T01:13:39Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThat is the longitude of the ascending node (or descending, depending on which way you\u0027re going). \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Kerbal Engineer Redux (mod)\u0022\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Kerbal Engineer Redux (mod)\u0022\u003EKER\u003C/abbr\u003E\u003C/abbr\u003E has it, \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Mechjeb (mod)\u0022\u003E\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Mechjeb (mod)\u0022\u003EMJ\u003C/abbr\u003E\u003C/abbr\u003E probably has it too.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022400px-Orbit1.svg.png\u0022 height=\u0022360\u0022 src=\u0022https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/Orbit1.svg/400px-Orbit1.svg.png\u0022 srcset=\u0022//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/Orbit1.svg/600px-Orbit1.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/eb/Orbit1.svg/800px-Orbit1.svg.png 2x\u0022 width=\u0022400\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nEDIT: to change it, you\u0027d have to burn normal/antinormal at the highest point of the orbit \u003Cem\u003Ein terms of latitude\u003C/em\u003E (not apoapsis). For example, the point on top of the blue line on the image above.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222016-08-07T01:17:50Z\u0022 title=\u002208/07/2016 01:17  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00227 yr\u0022\u003EAugust 7, 2016\u003C/time\u003E by Gaarst\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"elstak","CreatedById":161716,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-08-07T01:45:36Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nthank you man!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}